    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>March 2<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. 1882.—</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged to you for your kindness in having sent me a copy of your “Atlanttis”.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I shall read the book with interest, though I must confess in a very sceptical spirit.—</p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
              
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Donnelly argued in his recently published book, <hi rend="italic">Atlantis</hi> (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11718.xml">Donnelly 1882</ref>), that Atlantis was a real island, destroyed in a cataclysmic event; survivors travelled to all parts of the globe, carrying their tale of disaster, which became the various flood legends of widely separated cultures. For more on Donnelly and his literary output, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_11719.xml">Anderson 1980</ref>.</note>  
        </div>  
      
